==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: merge
<hw>merge</hw> <pr>(m⟦etil⟧rj)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Merged</conjf> <pr>(m⟦etil⟧rjd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Merging</conjf>
<pr>(m⟦etil⟧r"j⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>mergere</ets>,
<ets>mersum</ets>. Cf. <er>Emerge</er>, <er>Immerse</er>,
<er>Marrow</er>.]</ety> <def>To cause to be swallowed up; to immerse; to
sink; to absorb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>merge</qex> all natural . . . sentiment in inordinate
vanity.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whig and Tory were <qex>merged</qex> and swallowed up in the
transcendent duties of patriots.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Merge
<hw>Merge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be sunk, swallowed up, or
lost.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Native irresolution had <qex>merged</qex> in stronger motives.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>merged</ent>⟦br⟧
